  "notes": [
    "All transfer applicants must meet the University of California admissions eligibility requirements and the campus’s admission selection criteria. All requirements must be completed by the end of the spring term prior to transfer. For more information on UC admissions eligibility and admission to UC Santa Cruz, visit the Admissions website . The UC Santa Cruz Transfer Admission Guarantee (TAG) is a formal agreement that guarantees your fall admission to your chosen major, provided you are transferring from a California Community College and meet specific requirements. Visit the UC Santa Cruz TAG webpage for more information.",
    "THIS IS A SCREENING MAJOR. Screening majors require completion of specific preparatory coursework and/or a minimum GPA. For details on the specific screening requirements for this major, refer to the \" Transfer Admission Screening Policy \" below. Additional coursework listed under \"Recommended Preparation\" is not required for admission but is strongly recommended to support timely degree completion. For more information, including a list of screening majors and non-screening majors , visit the UCSC Admissions website.",
    "Some Advanced Placement (AP), International Baccalaureate Higher Level (IBH), and Advanced Level (A-level) exams satisfy UCSC course requirements. UCSC's exam credit policies may be found on the Degree Progress Unit website .",
    "Transfer students who want to pursue the technology and information management major, must have applied and been admitted to UC Santa Cruz as a proposed Technology and Information Management major. Transfer Admission Screening Policy Transfer applicants must complete the articulated equivalents of at least SIX of the courses listed in the \"Required Major Preparation Courses\" section below, with a cumulative GPA of 2.4 or better, no later than the end of the spring term prior to starting at UCSC in the fall. All attempted screening courses are included in the cumulative GPA. Courses completed via exam credit will count toward the minimum six courses required but are not included in the minimum GPA. While students may select any six courses from the list, it is strongly recommended that at least one be chosen from Computer Science and Engineering (CSE). Students planning to complete the degree within two years are advised to complete all screening courses except TIM 50, CSE 12, and CSE 13S. Additional Information for Transfer Students are also encouraged to complete the California General Education Transfer Curriculum (Cal-GETC) or all UC Santa Cruz general education requirements before transferring. For guidance on incorporating Cal-GETC into your academic plan, consult your community college counselor. Please visit the Baskin Engineering Undergraduate Experience website to learn more about this major. UC Santa Cruz General Catalog: Technology and Information Management B.S. Program Statement"
  ]
